node.text:
Thank you for sharing in our joy 💗. This video explains step by step how to create the green screen effect to make it look like the baby ultrasound is appearing over the skin as well as the gender reveal portion. 
The two video editing apps I used are Splice and Videoleap. You can use the same soundtrack by going to the original Reel video of the pregnancy announcement and clicking on the audio ❤️.

node.title: Pregnancy Announcement- How to create green screen effect

node.text: Come inside my car, well my husbands car (long story 😆), and watch Michelle from @safeintheseat share information on transitioning from one car seat to another, forward facing vs. front facing, booster seats vs harness car seats, and so much more. We even touched on the subject of carpool and fitting as many car seats as possible in the car. Really valuable safety information, thank you @safeintheseat 🚙❤️. Every week in October we will be sharing a safe activity to do in the car so keep a close eye out for that 🤗 #motherhood #momlife #safetyfirst #carseat #preschool #parenting #carsafety

Anyone else obsessed? 🙋🏻‍♀️ These are my top three favorite techniques. If I had to choose one, I would go with he ice technique. It gives it the coolest kaleidoscope look. Let me know which one is your favorite ❤️
•
🧊ICE TECHNIQUE🧊
1️⃣Soak your fabric in water and strain out any excess water. 
2️⃣Lay your shirt flat and use a fork to help create a swirl. Make two or three different swirls on the shirt. All in opposite directions. 
3️⃣Secure it using rubber bands
4️⃣Place the shirt on a rack with a bin underneath to catch any falling dye.
5️⃣Add a circular rim around the shirt to help hold ice in place. You can staple a piece of paper together to fit perfectly around the tied up shirt.
6️⃣Add ice on top of the shirt
7️⃣Sprinkle the dye powder onto of the ice. Note that it’s the dye powder, not the dye solution. Use one set of colors on one side of the shirt and another set on the other side.
8️⃣Wait for the ice to melt and turn the shirt over. Repeat steps 6 & 7.
9️⃣Place the shirt in a bag and wait at least 6 hours
🔟Remove the shirt from the bag and cut the rubber bands off.
1️⃣1️⃣Run the shirt under water until the water runs clear
1️⃣2️⃣Put the shirt to wash all on its own using cold water. Dry it and its all done 😃
•
❤️HEART DESIGN ❤️(minute 1:43)
1️⃣Soak your fabric in water and strain out any excess water. 
2️⃣Lay your shirt flat and fold in half. 
3️⃣Place a heart cut out on top and trace half of it onto the shirt using a washable marker. Very important it’s washable.
4️⃣Slowly crinkle the shirt together following the heart line. Ultimately the line must be straight for the design to work.
5️⃣Secure the shirt together by adding a rubber band around the line. Add more rubber bands as you go down the shirt. One section per color you want to use.
6️⃣Mix your dye powder with water and squirt it onto the shirt. One color per section. Make sure to get both sides.
7️⃣Place the shirt in a bag and wait at least 6 hours
8️⃣Remove the shirt from the bag and cut the rubber bands off.
9️⃣Run the shirt under water until the water runs clear
🔟Put the shirt to wash all on its own using cold water. Dry it and its all done 😃

node.text:
Quarantine edition 😉. My best tip for fostering independent play is having a clear and inviting play area. Whether it is in the living room, bedroom or its own designated play space, the room should feel and look like you yourself want to play in it. This method of rotating toys and cleaning up the play space once a month or every couple of months has changed our life at home and saved us a ton of money 😎. At the end of the video, I show how and where I store toys that are out of rotation and art supplies❤️. •
Even though I speak with confidence, I have no idea what I’m doing here 😂. This is just what works for us 😉. Whats your toy/play space situation like?
•
👉🏼That being said, let’s talk about setting up the play space😜. ❤️Furniture is key. Choose storage shelves with simple, clean lines. It helps make the area look organized even if it is cluttered with toys. I love open shelves such as the cubbed ones from Target as well as the Trofast system from Ikea (the one with white drawers).
🧡Separate your toys into 4. Store 3/4 of the toys and keep out only 1/4. 💛Always keep out favorite toys. Keep them out but move them around the play space to keep it fresh. 💚If you have 50 toy cars, only leave out 10 in the drawer. Repeat this for any toys you have a lot of. Store the rest and take them out every time you rotate the toys. 💙Get rid of all the small toys that really play no part. You know, the ones we get from birthday parties 😬. Just toss or donate them. Those are one and done toys. 💜Hall out toys your kids have outgrown. This one is particularly difficult as we tend to get emotionally attached to items that trigger memories. Baby toys are really hard to get rid of but it is necessary for keeping an organized play space. 💖Showcase toys as if you were in a storefront. Its clean, inviting and draws you right in. •
❣️You can find all of the toys in here on my Amazon page (link in bio)

node.title: Ocean sensory bin- made with stuff from around the house 🌊

node.text:
Do you feel like toys are taking over your house? 😅 Just slowly being swallowed by toys that no one really plays with? I so felt that way a couple of years ago. Miss matched toys everywhere. A lot of little bits here and there from random birthday parties and lost pieces all over the place. My girls weren’t even really playing with anything which made it even more annoying. I got fed up one day and literally got rid of half of their toys. I organized the rest and here we are today😍. This was a process. A long one but it has been the absolute best thing for us. My girls actually started playing independently and there’s no longer toys everywhere. It made our lives at home much more enjoyable 🤗
•
👉🏼What I did:
❤️Organized their toys into categories (Example: literacy, numeracy, pretend play, DIY, fine motor skills, Dolls, Kitchen/cooking, building, art, books). 🧡I split each category into four. Stored 3/4 of the toys and put out the rest for the girls to play with. This started the toy rotation system. Keep in mind that I always keep out absolute favorites and just change them around. 💛I rotate the toys from storage to the play space every month or so. This gives old toys new life and in return, we hardly ever buy new toys. 💚Rotation day is my day to deep clean and reorganize. Getting rid of all the little birthday party gifts 😉
💙Toy display is important. I showcase them like in a store. Clearly visible and decluttered. For example, take out a toy set from the box and put it on a flat tray. It entices you to play with it and keep it organized on a tray. Don’t over stuff drawers. Add just a few cars, not the whole collection.
💜Made a self serve art area. Having simple things like paper and markers available to them at their level has been amazing for independent playtime. •
There is so much more I want to tell you. Make sure to check out my stories today. Let me know if you have any questions. Answering them all in the comments ❤️ #mothercould

node.text: Neighborhood walks just got a little more fun 😜. Simply poke some holes in a piece of cardboard and you’ve got yourself a flower/leaf collection board 💐. Just make sure to make the holes big enough for little ones under 3 to able to easily insert the flowers 👌🏼. We tried this idea from @littlepinelearners last year and really loved collecting fallen flowers! My kids will often grab the vase boards before going on walks around the block. Tara’s page is packed with nature inspired ideas! Exactly what we need with Fall around the corner 🍃. #recycleandplay #kidsactivities #montessori #parenting #preschool #toddler #toddlerlife #momlife #motherhood #diy #crafty

node.text:
Change up the breakfast rotation with some Fluffy Pancakes! 🥞 They taste exactly as it sounds, almost like a pound cake 🤤. I call this a breakfast activity- making them is just as much fun as eating them 😋. So bouncy, SO good!! 
•
👉🏼 INGREDIENTS: 
- 1 cup flour 
- 1 tbsp baking powder
- 1 cup warm milk
- 1/4 cup melted butter 
- 1 egg
* Will make 2 large pancakes
👉🏼 INSTRUCTIONS:
1️⃣ Mix flour and baking powder in a bowl
2️⃣ Add the milk and melted butter to a separate bowl
3️⃣ Separate the egg yolk from the whites and add the yolk to the milk and butter. Mix well. 
4️⃣ In a third bowl, use a hand mixer to beat the egg whites on high until peaks form
5️⃣ Mix the wet ingredients with the dry ingredients then add in the egg whites. 
6️⃣ Heat a small frying pan and spray with oil. Add in 1-2 cups of batter and cover with a lid. Cook at medium to low heat. 
7️⃣ After 8 to 10 minutes, insert a toothpick to the center to see if it comes out clean. Transfer the pancake to a plate and repeat for the rest of the batter #easyrecipes #breakfastideas #toddlermeals #parenting #foodideas #motherhood #reels #momlife #instagram #toddlerlife #foodie

🖌 DIY SPONGE BRUSHES 🧽
Shoutout to that time I meticulously cut out shapes from old sponges 😜. See this as a way of making specialty sponge stamps like letters in a name. Fun cookie cutters are great to trace for this project! To use old sponges, soak it in water and put in the microwave for 1-2 mins, let them dry and you are ready to make some sponge brushes. If you prefer new ones, dollar tree has a pack of 2 for $1 🙌🏻.
•
👉🏼YOU’LL NEED:
-Sponges
-Marker/pen
-Scissors
-Knife
-Hot glue
-Popsicle sticks
👉🏼INSTRUCTIONS:
1️⃣Trace a shape on the sponge. I used a toy shape as a stencil. 
2️⃣Cut out the shape
3️⃣Make a slot in the center of the shape using the knife. Deep enough to insert the tip of a popsicle stick. 
4️⃣Cut a popsicle stick in half and add some hot glue to the tip. Insert it into the slot in the center of the shape. 
5️⃣Dip the sponge in paint and stamp on paper. 
💡Wash like you would any brush and leave out to dry. #mothercould #howto 
.

TASTE SAFE SLIME! Such a unique and fun texture to explore!! Put some chia seeds in the refrigerator now and you have yourself an activity in a few hours ❤️. This recipe makes a generous amount of slime so one can certainly be for siblings to share. The consistency is not exactly like traditional slime. It’s more like a mix between goop/oobleck and slime. It’s grainy because of the chia seeds and ohhh so fun to play with 🤗. 
•
👉🏼YOU’LL NEED:
-1/4 cup chia seeds
-1 3/4 cup water
-Food coloring 
-3-4 cups corn starch
👉🏼INSTRUCTIONS:
1️⃣ Mix the chia seeds, water and food coloring together.
2️⃣ Cover and refrigerate overnight. 
3️⃣ Uncover and add the corn starch a little at a time. About a cup at a time. Mix and then continue until you achieve the desired consistency. Should be like regular slime. Slimy but can be easily taken off the hands. 
4️⃣Store covered in the refrigerator. You will need to add a little water each time you take it out to use it. It will reactive the slime. 
•
❣️I’d love to know your thoughts on slime! 👍🏼or😝? #sensoryplay #kidsactivities #diy #slime #preschool #montessori #motherhood #parenting #toddlerlife #toddler #toddleractivities #momlife #crafty #learningthroughplay

Sunscreen 🤯. Save this post, you never know when you’ll need it 🙃. Yesterday I did an experiment in stories (saved to stains highlight) on how to remove permanent marker from walls (wall finish is eggshell). 
•
We tried sunscreen, rubbing alcohol, hand sanitizer, magic eraser, hair spray and dry erase marker over the permanent marker. Every single one of them failed except for the sunscreen. Most others removed the stain but also removed the paint from the wall. The sunscreen removed the stain while keeping the paint intact 🥳. Let’s just say if I was in the science fair, I would have won 😜. 
•
The sunscreen should be some sort of extra/maximum/sport strength for it to work. I tried one labeled for kids and it did not work. Tons of people wrote in saying that they tried it right away on old stains and it removed them instantly 🎉. #momhacks #parenting #momlife #motherhood #toddler #toddlerlife #kidsart #reels #lifehacks #cleaninghacks #cleaning #instagram #preschool #teacher #mothercould

node.text:
I had always imagined a beautifully calm and gently lighted picture of myself breastfeeding. You know, the same motherhood picture we’ve seen our entire lives? When I had my first, that picture crumbled faster than I could put it back together. I replaced a baby for pump parts and milk bags. It was nothing like I had imagined. 
•
I felt like such a failure. I took the classes, read the books, spoke to experienced mothers and still failed. I was lonely, angry, resentful and felt like no one understood the struggles. *It looked so easy for everyone else*
•
From flat nipples to latch issues, I pushed through bleeding sores for weeks, determined to breastfeed at all costs. It turns out that “at all costs” comes with a lot of trauma and damage. All this to achieve the aspiring image we paint for ourselves. My baby was thriving but I couldn’t see that through my own decay. 
•
Breastfeeding is a journey and it looks different for everyone. I didn’t know that until I went through it myself. I ended up exclusively pumping with both of my girls. It was the best decision mentally and physically for me. 
•
I wish I could go back in time and give myself a hug. Tell myself to trust my gut, let the guilt go and give myself a break because no matter how my babies were fed, it was going to be ok. For anyone struggling, feel my tight hug around you and this whisper in your ear. “We are doing our best ❤️”
•
Turn to caregivers who are nursing, formula feeding, tube feeding, combo feeding, pumping, using donor milk or any other feeding method and honor them ❤️. Let’s talk openly, share stories and emphasize all the ways we feed our babies!
•
A bit late to world breastfeeding week but what mom is ever on time? 🤪

🌋 FIZZY LETTERS 🔠
I took the classic baking soda and vinegar experiment and shaped it into letters for a fun alphabet sensory play activity 🤗. We sung the alphabet, pointed out to the letters in our names and watched the letters fizz over and over again 🤩. Tons of color recognition and mixing too! 🌈
•
👉🏼YOU’LL NEED:
-1 cup baking soda
-1tsp clear gelatin 
-1/4 cup water
-Alphabet cookie cutters/molds
-Vinegar
-Food coloring
👉🏼INSTRUCTIONS:
1️⃣Mix together the baking soda, gelatin powder and water to form a paste. Add a little more water if too dry. 
2️⃣Fill the alphabet molds with the paste. 
3️⃣Place all of the letters over parchment paper on a baking tray. 
4️⃣Freeze overnight. 
5️⃣Carefully push out the letters from the cookie cutters. 
Mix a bit of food coloring into vinegar and pour on top of the letters. Watch them fizz 🌋. 
💡Use a dropper for fine motor skill practice. #mothercould

node.text: Bubbles always make everything better 😜. Keep some handy for a quick pick me up when kids get antsy during long car rides.  Sometimes all you need is to change up the energy to keep going. And don’t worry, the bubbles pop in the air so you won’t have any residue on the seats. My husband approved and that says a lot 😉. Just make sure there’s no dripping from the wand before getting to the air vent. Use the back vents to keep away from the driver!
